<br>
I don't think many folks would claim EQ is a lifestyle.  Hobby or interest or pastime, sure.  Lifestyle, no.  It is certainly a game, though I think to say &quot;just&quot; a game is to do it a disservice.  Certainly, it is less important than many things in my life - my family, my boyfriend, my circle of friends, my education, my job, my students, etc. - but it *is* more important than some things.  To keep my subscription money, I limit how much I eat out, and I might pass up a new book or a pair of earrings or a new pair of jeans to have that money in my account to pay for EQ.  It's all relative.<br>
<br>
But...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And don't fool yourselves into thinking it's 'real'. Friends in EQ come and go, often with no warning.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Aye unless you meet the people irl and spend time with them irl, you can't really consider them a friend, because you don't really know them.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I call serious bullshit on these comments.  Admittedly, this is because of my own personal experiences and academic bent.  I'm a graduate student in communication theory.  My area of scholarly interest is interpersonal and relational communication online.  All contemporary theory and research is on my side in this instance, including firsthand research and experiences I've had myself.<br>
<br>
Relationships and friendships made via the Internet can be just as &quot;real&quot; (and by &quot;real&quot; I mean emotionally fulfilling and doing right by all of the needs we consider met by friendship) as face-to-face friendships.  Friends in EQ do come and go.  So do friends in &quot;real life.&quot;  I mean, I've only been out of high school 5 years and I've already completely lost touch with people I considered &quot;great friends&quot; in &quot;real life.&quot;  Not all of them.  But many.  Yet, I keep in touch with some friends I met on the internet 7 years ago, and have yet to meet &quot;in person.&quot;<br>
<br>
I met my boyfriend online nearly 4 years ago.  It took us two and a half years to meet in person (teh Atlantic Ocean and plane tix $$ suxxorz, k?) but our meeting was not some amazing revelation of who the other &quot;really was&quot; but a confirmation that our relationship was, well, as perfect as they come.  I got a smiling face that wasn't in a still picture and a warm hug to go along with everything, but it didn't change my feelings.<br>
<br>
And really, knowing someone &quot;IRL&quot; doesn't preclude them from turning out to be not at all the person you thought.  An acquaintance of mine seemed to be a really sweet, wonderful guy for the many years I knew him...and then (without going into sordid detail) he ended up doing some pretty awful, hateful, violent things to a friend of mine without any warning whatsoever.<br>
<br>
*sighs*  Okay, sure, I've gone off a bit.  It *is* important to keep in perspective that EQ is a game.  To dismiss the relationships we form with others in-game as meaningless, however, is missing the point entirely.<br>
<br>
